where $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ are nonnegative real numbers. 

Let $a = \frac 12 + x,$ $b = \frac 12 + z,$ and $c = \frac 12 - x - z.$ Then $x,$ $y,$ and $z$ are nonnegative real numbers satisfying $x + z \le \frac 12.$ We will show
\begin{align*}
\frac{(\frac 12 + x)(\frac 12 + z)}{\frac{1}{2} - x} + \frac{(\frac 12 + x)(\frac 12 - x - z)}{z} + \frac{(\frac 12 + z)(\frac 12 - x - z)}{x} &\le \frac{3}{4}, 
\end{align*}
which is equivalent to \begin{align*}
-\frac{4}{(x + \frac{1}{2})(z + \frac{1}{2})} + \frac{3}{x} + \frac{3}{z} + \frac{1}{xz} &\le 0.
\end{align*} Simplify the LHS, we get
\begin{align*}
-\frac{\frac{1}{4(xz + \frac 12 (x + z))}}{x + z - \frac{1}{2}} + \frac{3}{x} + \frac{3}{z} + \frac{1}{xz} &\le 0. 
